{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"17398149-e923-468c-a175-49833e5065bd","content":"The `dump-collect` skill I have available is specifically for **collecting** crash dumps, not analyzing them. For **analyzing** a `.dmp` file, here are the recommended tools:\n\n### `dotnet-dump analyze`\n```bash\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-dump\ndotnet-dump analyze <your-file.dmp>\n```\nUseful commands inside the analyzer:\n- `clrstack` — managed call stack\n- `pe` — print last exception\n- `dumpheap -stat` — heap summary\n- `threads` — list all threads\n\n### Other options\n- **Visual Studio** — open the `.dmp` directly for rich debugging\n- **lldb** (Linux) — with the SOS plugin for native + managed analysis\n- **WinDbg** (Windows) — with the SOS extension (`!analyze -v`)\n\nWould you like help setting up any of these tools in your current environment?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"2c811564-49df-4b9b-80f7-9cf33e11e6ab","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about analyzing a .dmp crash dump file. Let me check the available skills - there's a \"dump-collect\" skill, but its description specifically says:\n\n- USE FOR: enabling automatic crash dumps, capturing dumps, setting up dump collection\n- DO NOT USE FOR: analyzing or debugging dumps, post-mortem investigation with lldb/windbg/dotnet-dump analyze\n\nSo the dump-collect skill is NOT appropriate here. The user wants to analyze a dump, not collect one.\n\nLet me provide guidance on analyzing crash dumps directly.","outputTokens":347,"requestId":"981E:1380F:5AF055F:637A6B9:69F407B8"},"id":"ad0b7713-3393-4d63-82f9-7190788acd20","timestamp":"2026-05-01T01:54:09.919Z","parentId":"c798edf5-ee78-4aea-a8cd-eae79099a58d"}
